## 1. What Are Coroutines & Why Android Needs Them

Android apps run on the **Main Thread (UI Thread)**. Any long-running operation (network, database, file I/O) on the main thread causes **ANR (Application Not Responding)** errors.

### The Problem (Without Coroutines)

```kotlin
// ❌ BAD — blocks the Main Thread — causes ANR!
fun loadUserFromNetwork(): User {
    Thread.sleep(3000) // Simulates network call — freezes the UI!
    return User("John")
}
```

### The Traditional Fix (Messy)

```kotlin
// ❌ BAD — callback hell
fun loadUser(callback: (User) -> Unit) {
    Thread {
        val user = fetchFromServer() // blocking call on background thread
        runOnUiThread {
            callback(user) // back to main thread
        }
    }.start()
}
```

### The Coroutine Fix (Clean & Readable)

```kotlin
// ✅ GOOD — non-blocking, reads like synchronous code
fun loadUser() {
    viewModelScope.launch {
        val user = withContext(Dispatchers.IO) {
            fetchFromServer() // runs on background thread
        }
        updateUI(user) // automatically back on Main thread
    }
}
```

### Why Coroutines?

| Feature | Threads | Coroutines |
|---|---|---|
| Memory per unit | ~1 MB | ~100 bytes |
| Creation time | ~1 ms | ~1 µs |
| Code readability | Poor (callbacks) | Excellent (sequential) |
| Error handling | Complex | Natural try/catch |
| Cancellation | Manual | Built-in |
| Lifecycle-aware | No | Yes (via Scopes) |
| Max concurrent | ~1,000 | ~100,000+ |

