## 3. Core Coroutine Concepts

### Key Terms at a Glance

| Term | Meaning |
|---|---|
| `suspend` | Marks a function that can pause without blocking a thread |
| `CoroutineScope` | Defines the lifetime/boundary of coroutines |
| `CoroutineContext` | Carries metadata: Dispatcher + Job + Name |
| `Dispatcher` | Determines which thread the coroutine runs on |
| `Job` | Handle to a running coroutine; can cancel it |
| `launch` | Starts a coroutine and returns a `Job` |
| `async` | Starts a coroutine and returns a `Deferred<T>` (a future result) |
| `await()` | Suspends until `Deferred` has a result |
| `Flow` | A cold asynchronous stream of values |
| `StateFlow` | A hot flow that always holds the latest value (for UI state) |
| `Channel` | Hot communication pipe between coroutines |

### The Coroutine = Lightweight Thread Analogy

```kotlin
import kotlinx.coroutines.*

fun main() = runBlocking {
    // Launch 100,000 coroutines — no OutOfMemoryError!
    repeat(100_000) {
        launch {
            delay(1000L)
            print(".")
        }
    }
}
// Doing this with real threads would crash the app
```

