## 6. Coroutine Scopes in Android

A **CoroutineScope** defines the **lifetime** of coroutines. When the scope is cancelled, all coroutines inside it are cancelled too.

### 6.1 `viewModelScope` — For ViewModels ✅ Recommended

```kotlin
import androidx.lifecycle.ViewModel
import androidx.lifecycle.viewModelScope
import kotlinx.coroutines.*

class UserViewModel : ViewModel() {

    fun loadUser(id: Int) {
        // Automatically cancelled when ViewModel is cleared
        viewModelScope.launch {
            try {
                val user = withContext(Dispatchers.IO) {
                    userRepository.getUser(id)
                }
                _user.value = user
            } catch (e: Exception) {
                _error.value = e.message
            }
        }
    }

    // viewModelScope is automatically cancelled in onCleared()
    override fun onCleared() {
        super.onCleared()
        // No manual cleanup needed!
    }
}
```

### 6.2 `lifecycleScope` — For Activities & Fragments ✅ Recommended

```kotlin
import androidx.lifecycle.lifecycleScope
import kotlinx.coroutines.*

class MainActivity : AppCompatActivity() {

    override fun onCreate(savedInstanceState: Bundle?) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState)

        // Cancelled when Activity is DESTROYED
        lifecycleScope.launch {
            val data = fetchData()
            textView.text = data
        }
    }
}

class UserFragment : Fragment() {

    override fun onViewCreated(view: View, savedInstanceState: Bundle?) {
        super.onViewCreated(view, savedInstanceState)

        // Cancelled when Fragment's VIEW is DESTROYED
        viewLifecycleOwner.lifecycleScope.launch {
            val data = fetchData()
            binding.textView.text = data
        }
    }
}
```

### 6.3 `repeatOnLifecycle` — Lifecycle-Safe Collection

```kotlin
class UserFragment : Fragment() {

    private val viewModel: UserViewModel by viewModels()

    override fun onViewCreated(view: View, savedInstanceState: Bundle?) {
        super.onViewCreated(view, savedInstanceState)

        // BEST PRACTICE for collecting Flow in Fragments/Activities
        viewLifecycleOwner.lifecycleScope.launch {
            // Starts when STARTED, stops when STOPPED, restarts when STARTED again
            viewLifecycleOwner.repeatOnLifecycle(Lifecycle.State.STARTED) {
                viewModel.uiState.collect { state ->
                    renderUi(state)
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```

### 6.4 Custom CoroutineScope — For Services

```kotlin
import kotlinx.coroutines.*

class MyForegroundService : Service() {

    // Create a custom scope tied to the service lifecycle
    private val serviceScope = CoroutineScope(Dispatchers.Default + SupervisorJob())

    override fun onStartCommand(intent: Intent?, flags: Int, startId: Int): Int {
        serviceScope.launch {
            doLongRunningWork()
        }
        return START_NOT_STICKY
    }

    override fun onDestroy() {
        super.onDestroy()
        serviceScope.cancel() // Cancel all coroutines when service is destroyed
    }
}
```

### Scope Lifecycle Summary

| Scope | Cancelled When | Use For |
|---|---|---|
| `viewModelScope` | `ViewModel.onCleared()` | Data loading, business logic |
| `lifecycleScope` | `Activity/Fragment.onDestroy()` | UI operations |
| `viewLifecycleOwner.lifecycleScope` | Fragment view destroyed | Fragment UI updates |
| Custom scope | You call `.cancel()` | Services, custom classes |
| `GlobalScope` | App process ends | ⚠️ Avoid — causes leaks |

